Polynomial Regression, and Evaluation using R-Squared, MAPE and MAE.

Goal

We goal is to create a tool that predicts the chances of diabetes getting worse using Body Mass Index (BMI) feature within the dataset. This tool will help doctors identify patients who might be at risk.

The source of the data is from stat.ncsu.edu hosted on Scikit-Learn: Diabetes (Toy Dataset)

Diabetes dataset
----------------

Ten baseline variables, age, sex, body mass index, average blood
pressure, and six blood serum measurements were obtained for each of n =
442 diabetes patients, as well as the response of interest, a
quantitative measure of disease progression one year after baseline.

**Data Set Characteristics:**

  :Number of Instances: 442

  :Number of Attributes: First 10 columns are numeric predictive values

  :Target: Column 11 is a quantitative measure of disease progression one year after baseline

  :Attribute Information:
      - age     age in years
      - sex
      - bmi     body mass index
      - bp      average blood pressure
      - s1      tc, total serum cholesterol
      - s2      ldl, low-density lipoproteins
      - s3      hdl, high-density lipoproteins
      - s4      tch, total cholesterol / HDL
      - s5      ltg, possibly log of serum triglycerides level
      - s6      glu, blood sugar level

Note: Each of these 10 feature variables have been mean centered and scaled by the standard deviation times the square root of `n_samples` (i.e. the sum of squares of each column totals 1).

Source URL:
https://www4.stat.ncsu.edu/~boos/var.select/diabetes.html

def create_polynomial_model(degree, X, y):
    poly_features = PolynomialFeatures(degree=degree, include_bias=False)
    X_poly = poly_features.fit_transform(X)

    model = LinearRegression()
    model.fit(X_poly, y)
    
    return model, X_poly

def print_model_stats(model):
    if isinstance(model, Pipeline):
        linear_model = model.named_steps['linear']
    else:
        linear_model = model

    print(f'Model: {linear_model}')
    print(f'Coefficients: {linear_model.coef_}')
    print(f'Intercept: {linear_model.intercept_}')

    equation = f"y = {linear_model.intercept_:.2f}"
    for i, coef in enumerate(linear_model.coef_):
        equation += f" + {coef:.2f} * X^{i+1}"
    print(f'Equation: {equation}')

def print_pipeline_model_stats(model, deg):
    linear_model = model.named_steps['linear']
    poly_features = model.named_steps['polynomial']

    print(f'\nDegree {deg}')
    print(f'Coefficients: {linear_model.coef_}')
    print(f'Intercept: {linear_model.intercept_}')

    equation = f"y = {linear_model.intercept_:.2f}" +''.join([f" + {coef:.2f} * X^{i+1}"for i, coef in enumerate(linear_model.coef_)])
    print(f'Equation: {equation}\n')

def plot_model(X, y, model):
    if not isinstance(X, pd.DataFrame):
        X = pd.DataFrame(X, columns=["bmi"])

    X_bmi = X["bmi"].values

    X_bmi = np.asarray(X_bmi).reshape(-1, 1)
    y = np.asarray(y)

    y_pred = model.predict(X_bmi)

    plt.scatter(X_bmi, y, color='blue', label='Data')

    plt.plot(X_bmi, y_pred, color='red', label='Model Fit')

    plt.xlabel('BMI')
    plt.ylabel('Disease Progression')
    plt.title('Model Fit')
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()
In[72]:
def create_polynomial_models(X: np.ndarray, y: np.ndarray, degrees: List[int]) -> dict[int, np.poly1d]:
    """
    Creates polynomial models for the given degrees and fits them to the given data.

    Args
        X: The x values of the data.
        y: The y values of the data.
        degrees: A list of polynomial degrees to try.

    Returns:
        A dictionary of polynomial models, with the polynomial degree as the key.
    """

    models = {}
    for degree in degrees:
        model = Pipeline([('polynomial', PolynomialFeatures(degree=degree)),
                          ('linear', LinearRegression())])
        model.fit(X, y)
        models[degree] = model
    return models

def print_model_metrics(y_true, y_pred, dataset_name, model_name):
    r2 = r2_score(y_true, y_pred)
    mae = mean_absolute_error(y_true, y_pred)
    mape = mean_absolute_percentage_error(y_true, y_pred)
    
    print(f'\nMetrics for Model {model_name} on {dataset_name} dataset:')
    print(f'R-squared: {r2:.4f}')
    print(f'MAE: {mae:.4f}')
    print(f'MAPE: {mape:.4f}\n')

def plot_multiple_models(X_train, y_train, X_val, y_val, models):
    X_continuous = np.linspace(min(X_train), max(X_train), 100).reshape(-1, 1)
    
    for name, model in models.items():
    
        plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
        
    
        plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
        plt.scatter(X_train, y_train, s=20, edgecolor="black", c="silver", label="Training Data")
        plt.plot(X_continuous, model.predict(X_continuous), label=f"Model={name}", linewidth=2)
        plt.xlabel("BMI")
        plt.ylabel("Target")
        plt.title(f"Model={name} - Training Dataset")
        plt.legend()

    
        plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
        plt.scatter(X_val, y_val, s=20, edgecolor="black", c="silver", label="Validation Data")
        plt.plot(X_continuous, model.predict(X_continuous), label=f"Model={name}", linewidth=2)
        plt.xlabel("BMI")
        plt.ylabel("Target")
        plt.title(f"Model={name} - Validation Dataset")
        plt.legend()


        plt.tight_layout()
        plt.show()
    
        y_train_pred = model.predict(X_train)
        print_model_metrics(y_train, y_train_pred, 'Training', name)

    
        y_val_pred = model.predict(X_val)
        print_model_metrics(y_val, y_val_pred, 'Validation', name)

        print("----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------")

plot_multiple_models(X_train, y_train, X_val, y_val, models)

Choosing the Best Model

In[77]:
best_model_name = None
best_model_r2_val = -float('inf')

for name, model in models.items():
    y_train_pred = model.predict(X_train)
    r2_train = r2_score(y_train, y_train_pred)

    y_val_pred = model.predict(X_val)
    r2_val = r2_score(y_val, y_val_pred)

    if r2_val > best_model_r2_val:
        best_model_r2_val = r2_val
        best_model_name = name
print(f"\nBest Model of Fit (based on R-squared on Validation Dataset): {best_model_name}")

Best Model of Fit (based on R-squared on Validation Dataset): 5

  • We can picking the best model by looking at the following choices using some important measures:

  • R-squared shows how good a model is at explaining things; higher is better.

  • Mean Absolute Error (MAE) tells us how close a model's guesses are to the real predictions, lower MAE is preferrable.

  • Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE) shows how accurate predictions are in percentages.

  • Model 5 does scores better, with more R-squared, lower MAE, and MAPE.

  • Model 5 is great at explaining, making accurate predictions, and staying consistent in both training and testing.

Manual VS Prediction

In[81]:
best_model = models[best_model_name]

intercept = best_model.named_steps['linear'].intercept_
coefficients = best_model.named_steps['linear'].coef_

bmi_value_1 = 0.1
bmi_value_2 = 30

manual_prediction_1 = intercept + sum(coef * (bmi_value_1 ** (i + 1)) for i, coef in enumerate(coefficients))
manual_prediction_2 = intercept + sum(coef * (bmi_value_2 ** (i + 1)) for i, coef in enumerate(coefficients))

model_prediction_1 = best_model.predict([[bmi_value_1]])[0]
model_prediction_2 = best_model.predict([[bmi_value_2]])[0]

print(f"Manual Prediction: {manual_prediction_1:.2f}")
print(f"Model Prediction: {model_prediction_1:.2f}")

print(f"Manual Prediction: {manual_prediction_2:.2f}")
print(f"Model Prediction: {model_prediction_2:.2f}")

Manual Prediction: 164.45
Model Prediction: 252.18
Manual Prediction: -3449137627753438.50
Model Prediction: -114971254258298.41

  • We can observe that the prediction vary significantly: the first two are reasonable, but the latter two have a huge difference, with a highly negative manual prediction.

  • The difference in predictions happens because the model was trained on BMI values that were made smaller. This makes the model better at predicting for smaller BMI values, but not so good for bigger BMI values.

  • To make the predictions better, we need to really look at the numbers we're using, check how the model was taught, and think about how making the numbers smaller might affect our predictions, and scale the actual dataset back to normal to make accurate predictions.

  • We can also notice that according to the data set as the BMI increases the frequncy of the Target variable increases which indicates towards higher number of cases which are related with higher blood pressure which mimics towards the real life scenario which makes the model reliable and trained on accurate data.

  • We can conclude that the current model is trained as per the resources available and needs improvements to make it more reliable and accurate.
